use lib '../lib';
use App::bsky;
exit App::bsky::CLI->new->run(@ARGV);
__END__

=encoding utf-8

=head1 NAME

bsky - A Command-line Bluesky Client

=head1 SYNOPSIS

    # create user session
    $ bsky login [handle] [password]

    # view recent posts
    $ bsky timeline ...

    # create a post
    $ bsky post ...

=head1 DESCRIPTION

C<bsky> is a simple command line client for Bluesky in Perl.

=head1 Usage

   bsky [global options] command [command options] [arguments...]

=head1 Commands

=head2 show-profile

show profile

=head2 update-profile

update profile

=head2 timeline

    bsky timeline

    bsky timeline --json

Display posts from timeline.

=head3 Options

    --json      boolean flag; content is printed as JSON objects if given

=head2 thread

show thread

=head2 post

post new text

=head2 vote

    bsky vote [uri] [bool]

Vote on the post

=head3 Options

    uri
    bool      optional, a true value (the default) votes the post up, an untrue value is a downvote

=head2 votes

    bsky votes [uri]

Show votes of the post.

=head3 Options

    uri

=head2 repost

    bsky repost [uri]

Repost the post

=head3 Options

    uri

=head2 reposts

    bsky reposts [uri]

Show reposts of the post

=head3 Options

    uri

=head2 follow

    bsky follow [handle]

Follow the handle

=head3 Options

    handle

=head2 follows

    bsky follows [user]

Show follows.

=head3 Options

    user        optional, defaults to the current logged in account

=head2 followers

    bsky followers [user]

Show followers.

=head3 Options

    user        optional, defaults to the current logged in account

=head2 delete

    bsky delete [cid]

Delete an item.

=head3 Options

    cid

=head2 login

    bsky login [ident] [password] [host]

Log into a Bluesky account.

=head3 Options

    ident
    password
    host        optional, defaults to https://bsky.social]

=head2 help

shows a list of commands or help for one command

=head1 Global Options

   -a value       profile name
   -V             verbose (default: false)
   --help, -h     show help
   --version, -v  print the version

=head1 See Also

L<At>.pm

L<https://github.com/mattn/bsky> - Original Golang client

